## Reference Example

```ts
// Declare file-scoped function params separately
type Params = {
  param1: string;
  param2?: number;
}

function fileScopedFunction = ({ param1, param2 }: Params) => {
  // ...
}

// Declare component props separately
type Item = {
  id: string;
  label: string;
};

type Props = {
  items: Item[];
  title: string;
};

const MyComponent = ({ items, title }: Props) => {
  // Be pragmatic about inline functions
  const inlineFunction = ({ param1, param2 }: { param1: string, param2: number }) = {
    // ...
  }

  fileScopedFunction({ param1: 'arg', param2: 7 });
  inlineFunction({ param1: 'arg', param2: 7 });

  return (
     // ...
  );
};
```

### Declaring Prop Types

#### React Components

In the interests of readability and consistency, declare props for a component in their own type declaration; not inline. If you intend on exporting the type, please prefix it with the name of the component.

```ts
// Prefer
type Props = {
  title: string;
};

const Component = ({ title }: Props) => {
  /* ... */
};

// Do not prefer
const Component = ({ title }: { title: string }) => {
  /* ... */
};

// When exporting
export type MyComponentProps = {
  title: string;
};

// note that the consumer could also use React.ComponentProps<MyComponent> instead, when appropriate

const MyComponent = ({ title }: MyComponentProps) => {
  /* ... */
};
```

#### Hooks/Functions

When applicable, declare any arguments that are object-types outside of the function signature, akin to React Components. When naming, prefer suffixing with `Params` instead of `Props`, as props should be reserved for React Components.

```ts
type SomeObject = {
  name: string;
  age: number;
};

// Prefer
const useSomeObjectHook = ({ name, age }: SomeObject) => {
  /* ... */
};

// Do not prefer
const useSomeObjectHook = ({ name, age }: {name: string, age: number}) => {
  /* ... */
}/
```

Functions declared inline (within components or other functions) should be handled pragmatically.

```ts
type Params = {
  // many params
}

const Component = () => {
  const declaredInline = ({ x, y }: { x: number, y: number }) => {/* ... */}
  const alsoInline = ({ ..aMillionParams }: Params) => {/* ... */}
  return (
    // ...
  )
}

```

When writing utility functions, it is preferable to pass in primitives as parameters instead of within objects

```ts
// Prefer
const toUpperCase = (title: string) => {
  /* ... */
};

// This is unnecessarily complex

type Params = {
  title: string;
};

const toUpperCase = ({ title }: Params) => {
  /* ... */
};
```

### Types vs Interfaces

#### When should I use a type?

Use types by default. Don't prepend types with `I` e.g. IProps. The project may currently feature some interfaces, but we are phasing those out.

```ts
// prefer
type Props = {
  // ...props
};

// do not prefer
interface IComponentProps {
  // ...props
}

// don't be a monster
type IComponentProps = {
  // ...props
};
```

#### When should I use an interface?

Use interfaces when:

- You intend for an API to be globally extendable; such as these examples with i18next, or Cypress. We can't really think of any use cases within the project code, but feel free to prove us wrong!

```ts
declare module 'react-i18next' {
  interface CustomTypeOptions {
    defaultNS: 'common';
    resources: {
      accounts: typeof accounts;
      actionMenu: typeof actionMenu;
    };
  }
}
```

```ts
declare global {
  namespace Cypress {
    interface Chainable {
      /**
       * Custom command to select DOM element by data-cy attribute.
       * @example cy.dataCy('greeting')
       */
      dataCy(value: string): Chainable<Element>;
    }
  }
}
```

